Here's an example of how you could create a simple web app that displays the contents of a local file named "local.txt" using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Local File Viewer</title>
    <style>
      body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: center;
        height: 100vh;
        background-color: #f5f5f5;
      }
      pre {
        white-space: pre-wrap;
        word-wrap: break-word;
        background-color: white;
        border: 1px solid #ddd;
        padding: 1rem;
        max-width: 80%;
        overflow-x: auto;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <pre id="fileContent"></pre>
    <script>
      const fileContent = document.getElementById('fileContent');
      const loadFile = async () => {
        try {
          const response = await fetch('local.txt');
          if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error(`Error loading file: ${response.status}`);
          }
          const text = await response.text();
          fileContent.textContent = text;
        } catch (error) {
          console.error(error);
          fileContent.textContent = 'Failed to load file.';
        }
      };
      loadFile();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

This code creates a basic HTML page with a `pre` element to display the contents of the file. The CSS styles the page and the `pre` element to make it look better.
The JavaScript uses the Fetch API to load the contents of the file from the local filesystem, and then updates the `textContent` property of the `pre` element with the loaded text.
Note that due to security restrictions, this code may not work when run directly from the local filesystem. Instead, you should serve it from a local web server or from a remote server.
